beer_description: This wonderful beer has a deep golden hue and a smooth malty flavor with a clean pleasant finish. Imported German malts are used to create the flavor of this festive beer.
Our tribute to the town we consider to be \Gonzo Ground Zero\"... Woody Creek White is a traditional Belgian-style Wit Beer

This summer seasonal is a slightly tart, refreshing pale ale made with raspberries, blueberries and other natural fruit juices.  Just as the cinnamon black bear on our label craves the flavor of mountain tundra berries, you?ll find our Tundrabeary Ale to be irresistibly delicious.

1995 Gold Medal, Best Fruit Beer, Colorado Springs Beer Fest.

Our interpretation of this classic and refreshing Belgian style Wit ale is brewed with organic pilsner and wheat malts from Canada. Freshly ground coriander and Curacao orange peel along with a special Wit yeast strain contribute wonderful orange and citrus aromas and a crisp, yet silky mouthfeel.

Originally brewed in 2009 to celebrate Specialty Imports? 30th Anniversary, XXX Black Double IPA is now produced each winter. XXX offers bold, American hop character ? comfortably cloaked in dark, luxurious malt. This exciting ?winter warmer? will take the chill right out of your bones. Curl up with this session-beer-meets-nightcap.

Sometimes XXX just means 30.

With passion & purpose, we present this series of experimental hop-driven beers. Using different hop varieties & brewing techniques, we aim to educate the palate & challenge the hophead in you.

Obliteration VI is a Double IPA brewed with Summit, Summit and Summit; 95 IBU???s
Jack Whacker Wheat Ale is a light, unfiltered brew with a citrus aroma and flavor imparted by a late addition of lemon grass. It's the perfect refreshment for a thirsty, trail-weary ale lover.

The Wulff is styled after the Austrian Kristall Weizen, a clear and filtered wheat beer. Unlike many low gravity bottled wheats, the Wulff shares the bluster and flare of its namesake fly, having a high starting gravity for the style.
This beer is dark because the barley is roasted longer? a flavorful lager that everyone will enjoy.
This dry stout features a roasty coffee-like bitterness and a clean well balanced palate. A gentle hop bitterness is present.
A soft yet balanced Irish red with caramel notes
This light brown ale is brewed with a small amount of chocolate malt which gives the ale its rich dark color. Mount Hood and Willamette hops provide aroma and bitterness.
A light crisp, refreshing and drinkable ale featuring the finest Saaz hops the Czech Republic has to offer.

Our most robust offering. Brewed with dark malts like Chocolate and Caramel, roasted barley and just a hint of peat-smoked malt. Buffalo Stout is surprisingly light with coffee-like undertones and a rich creamy texture.
Brewed with caramel malt for a flavorful depth of character, and four kinds of hops for a pleasant aroma and taste. Ringneck Red is a medium-bodied beer with a rich red color.
A smooth ale brewed with two-row barley malt, two domestic hops and locally produced clover honey. This ale is brewed exclusively for the Midnight Star Saloon in Deadwood, SD.

This traditional Belgian saison (say-sawn) style summer ale is deep golden, light-bodied, cloudy, and features the fruity nose and complex, spicy flavor which are the handiwork of a classic Belgian yeast strain. Made with pilsner malt, Belgian sugar, and two cereal grains, this is a strong yet refreshing summer thirst-quencher.
A dry oatmeal stout. Coffee, roast and chocolate flavors throughout, very smooth body from the addition of flaked oats. The use of six different malts makes this a very complex beer.
Southern English style of brown ale. Caramel, chocolate, slightly roasty flavors dominate the profile of this beer. Brewed to be flavorful and highly drinkable at the same time.
Amber coloured top-fermented abbey beer.

Unfiltered top-fermented beer.

Review of the Brussels Beer Challenge 2015:
Appearance: Blond colour with a big white head, good lacing, good head retention, OK carbonation. 
Aroma: Citrus, pear, apple. Great nose. 
Taste & body: Medium body, OK carbontion on the palate, round mouth feel, fruity, spicy, yeasty, a touch of malt and hops. Very typical. Dry finale. Very drinkable and very balanced. Excellent beer.

The Bush de No?l derives much of its rounded character from the use of roast caramel malts. The hops are carefully balanced with these, added in just the right proportions to develops its subtle hop aroma. There is also a robust fruity character, with the overall taste pleasingly consistent.

beer_description:
Delicate and devilishly drinkable, this quintessentially Kentish ale lays the county's hallowed, herbaceous hops on a firm, biscuity bed of pale and crystal malt. Endowed with an inviting auburn-amber hue and a tantalising toffee-ish aroma, it's an enlivening English ale that, given its unassuming ABV, pleasures the palate with a remarkable fullness of flavour.

Bottles - 4%
Cask - 3.7%

A pale copper coloured, rewarding beer brewed with pale and crystal malts and hopped with English Goldings and American Liberty hops. The aroma booms with peppery hops and bitter oranges, balanced by fresh bread maltiness. Hops and fruit dominate the palate, while the finish has sappy malt, tart fruit and lingering hop bitterness.

This 4.2% Kentish ale (bottle 4.5%) was first brewed in 1990 to celebrate the Battle of Britain which was fought in the skies above Kent 50 years earlier. The beer is named after the legendary Spitfire aeroplane designed by RJ Mitchell. The versatility of the aircraft and the courage of its pilots were essential to victory and were a key symbol of the spirit of that time.

Amber Ale has a deep amber color topped with an ample two finger white head. The great head retention and fishnet lacing add to the ambiance of this ale. With the faint citric hop aroma mixed with sweet caramel malt, the body supports a nice balance between malt and hop. It's a medium bodied ale with a creamy mouthfeel that finishes very clean.

Pub Draught has a thick, creamy head that rests on top of a hazy amber beer. The head is massive and lasting. Pub Draught has a smooth aroma of light English hops, along with a faint fruit smell. The aroma hints at the taste of flaky biscuit-like toasted malts with a hint of toffee and mild English hops. With as satisfyingly refreshing quality, it's about as smooth, creamy, and drinkable as a beer can get.
Rich caramel malts and a touch of roasted barley create the distinctive flavor of this Irish Red Ale, the namesake of Packers great Johnny ?Blood? McNally.
This German-style amber ale balances rich, toasty malt and crisp, aromatic noble hops. Clean yet robust, rich yet sessionable. Silver medalist in the Great American Beer Festival.
Toasty malt and plenty of local wildflower honey make this golden blonde ale one of our most popular beers. Named after the famous "400" Chicago and Northwestern passenger train.
Brewed with 50 pounds of oatmeal in every batch, we combine this with a blend of roasted barley, chocolate and black patent malts to create a rich, creamy and smooth ale.
Malted barley and a generous amount of crystal malt. This amber colored ale is slightly sweet and easy drinking.
Pale Ale, Maris Otter, Carapils, and Carastan malts. Cascade and Centennial hops. Clean and crisp with loads of floral and tropical fruit aromas and flavors.
An American style wheat beer which combines malted barley with wheat malt. This gold colored beer is very light and refreshing. A great introduction to craft-brewed beer.
A roasted smokey taste with medium hoppiness earmarks this as a smooth Sweet Stout. Its thick rich head is characteristic of all Stouts.
A traditional amber pale ale, a bit hoppier than the Off the Rail.
This Amber Pale Ale has a light to medium body. A well blanced malt to hop profile gives it that crisp thirst quenching flavor.
Wigged Pig is a light golden wheat beer with light body and light hoppiness (bitterness). It has a slightly crisp taste making it quite refreshing on a warm day.

This name comes from the notorious red light district of some 100 years ago in which Front Street Brewery is located. An extra dark, almost black bottom brew, smooth with a slight coffee flavor, achieved by the use of highly roasted barley and black malts. This beer is known as the espresso of beers. Bucktown soon becomes the favorite of the adventuresome.

A commemorative brew named after the great flood of '93. This is a bronze colored beer made with the highest quality malts and specially chosen hops to give this beer that extra hop bitterness with a delightful hop bouquet. A true "APA."
We start with an American light beer, lightly hopped, using only the finest hops. Cherry is then added to this beer and aged in our beer cellar, producing a delightful, refreshing taste and aroma.

A German Style Hefeweizen. The malts used were 60% Pilsner and 40% Wheat. Spalt hops were used subtly. What makes this wheat beer unique is the yeast strain used. It gives the beer Banana, Clove and citrus flavors. This beer is an unfiltered beer and the large portion of wheat makes this beer very hazy, which is how it?s supposed to be. No lemon is required for this beer. All a lemon does is dissipate the foamy head of the beer. Plus there are no lemon trees in Germany so you wouldn?t catch a German adding a lemon to a finely made Hefe. El Jefe in Spanish means the Boss.  This beer is truly "The Boss"

A light gold beer brewed with great care using barley malts and just the right amount of hops to give the beer its smooth, balanced taste and style belonging only to a beer of superior quality. This beer is particularly light and refreshing.

Named after the Dorset Horn ram that lived in the brewery stables in Wandsworth, and on which the Young?s trademark is based ? a proven symbol of Young?s brewing heritage and a firm favourite with drinkers for over 30 years.

Ram Rod is a 100% malt brew with Maris Otter and Crystal malt and Fuggle and Golding hops.

Young's Ram Rod is available as an Autumn seasonal cask beer during September and October.

A resurrection of an early brewing technique used in the days before iron kettles, when brewers heated wort by dropping fire-heated rocks into wooden vessels. Brimstone Brewing Company revived this arduous process, which had been abandoned for centuries, in 1994. The intense heat from the rocks caramelizes wort sugars, which later release toffee-like flavors into the beer. Its dry, crisp finish and complex, malty flavors can be enjoyed year-round.

Brewed with two-row malt, Munich malt, dark roasted caramel, and chocolate malts, this Doppelbock is based on the beer that won a silver medal at the Great American Beer Festival. A deep, auburn brown hue hints at the complex caramel malt taste, accented by its big body, slightly spicy and sweet aftertaste, and softly hopped finish. It is a thick but balanced and drinkable dark lager, well aged. Hopped with Northern Brewer and Tettnang.
